                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.000/3005.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 29, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: When I had the pleasure of
                    seeing you yesterday you said that the Mexican Government had decided to close
                    Juárez to international commerce, and that you were instructed to request that
                    the Government of the United States give orders to the Federal authorities in El
                    Paso absolutely to prevent shipments of contraband of war to the
                    insurrectionists in Juárez.</p>
                <p>It will at once be evident to your excellency’s Government that the suggestion
                    now made regarding contraband of war would immediately involve such
                    considerations as that whether, in fact, there was a state of belligerency in
                    the present situation.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
